The Federal Capital Territory Administration (FCTA) has commenced the decontamination of the city as part of measures to combat the spread of the coronavirus pandemic in the territory.  Minister of state for the Federal Capital Territory (FCT), Dr. Ramatu Tijjani Aliyu, who flagged off the exercise at the Berger Roundabout at the weekend, called for inter-agency collaboration to achieve the desired results in the battle against COVID-19.  Aliyu assured FCT residents that they are in safe hands, as government would continue to do everything possible to contain the spread of the virus, just as she stressed that nation building is a collective responsibility.  “We are here to symbolically flag-off the decontamination of the city starting from the Berger junction. This spot is very significant because it is a point of convergence. This is where you find the hustling and bustling.  “As you can see today, the entire stakeholders are united in this battle against COVID-19. You can see the Nigeria Police, Nigerian Security and Civil Defense Corps, Federal Road Safety Corps, Fire Fighters, and organised private sector are here in this fight and we will take it to all the nooks and crannies of the city. And from there we will move to all the satellite towns as well.”  Earlier in his remarks, the director of Abuja Environmental Protection Board (AEPB), Mallam Baba Shehu Lawan, had called on residents to cooperate with the authorities throughout the duration of the fumigation exercise, adding that the chemicals are eco and human friendly.  